      "title": "Bouncing Simulator",
      "topics": [],
      "solution": "w, h = int(input()), int(input())\nbounces = int(input())\n\ngrid = [list(\"#\"*(w+2))] + [[]] * h + [list(\"#\"*(w+2))]\nstart = [1, 1]\ndirec = [1, 1]\n\nfor i in range(1, h+1):\n    grid[i] = list(\"#\" + \" \" * w + \"#\")\n    \nwhile bounces:\n    v = grid[start[0]][start[1]]\n    vy, vx = start\n    bounced = False\n    grid[vy][vx] = \"1\" if v == \" \" else str(int(v)+1)\n    if grid[vy + direc[0]][vx] == \"#\": direc[0] *= -1; bounces -= bounced == False; bounced = True\n    if grid[vy][vx + direc[1]] == \"#\": direc[1] *= -1; bounces -= bounced == False; bounced = True\n    start = [vy + (direc[0] if grid[vy + direc[0]][vx] != \"#\" else 0), vx + (direc[1] if grid[vy][vx + direc[1]] != \"#\" else 0)]\n\nfor r in grid:\n    print(*r, sep = \"\")",
      "statement": "Your aim is to simulate a ball bouncing in a closed container of width [[w]] and height [[h]] (excluding the area covered by the boundary) after [[n]] number of hits. The ASCII representation of the box has a boundary drawn by hashes ({{#}})\nThe ball starts from the top-left of the container and moves south-east, changing its direction depending on the surface it hits.\nThe path of the ball is to be marked by numbers, denoting the number of times the ball has passed through that point.\n<<Note:>> If the ball is stuck in a narrow box (either of the dimensions is 1) then it passes along the box rather than bouncing (it bounces but it is barely visible due to the resolution).",
